04275nam a22007455i 9781442621022DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426210227 a10.3138/97814426210222doi  a(DE-B1597)465513  a(OCoLC)946712950  a(OCoLC)999354672  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aREL0670702bisacsh04aThe Mirroure of the Worlde :bA Middle English Translation of the Miroir de Monde /cRuth Sternglantz, Elaine Whitaker, Robert Raymo. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2003  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedieval Academy Books00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations and Sigla -- tIntroduction -- tThe Mirroure of the Worlds -- tHere Begynneth the Chapitres of the Booke That is Called the Mirroure of the Worlde and That Some Calleth Vice and Vertu. Part 1 -- tHere Begynneth The Chapitres Of The Booke That Is Called The Mirroure Of The Worlde And That Some Calleth Vice And Vertu. Part 2 -- tTextual Notes -- tExplanatory Notes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe allegories of the virtues and vices were a common teaching tool in the Middle Ages for both religious and lay audiences to learn the basic tenets of the Christian faith. The Mirroure of the Worlde makes available for the first time the unique text in the fifteenth-century British manuscript, MS. Bodley 283, which is among the last and largest works in the tradition of lay religious instruction mandated by the Fourth Lateran Council. The Mirroure is derived from conflations of the Miroir du Monde and the Somme le Roi, both vernacular treatises on vices and virtues compiled in Northeast France in the thirteenth century. Translated into Middle English by, it is believed, Stephen Scrope, the foremost English translator of the mid-fifteenth century, this edition is one of the only books of virtues and vices that contains Latin text, an inclusion that points towards a more widespread knowledge of the language among the laypeople than previously thought. Complete with explanatory notes and a glossary, The Mirroure of the Worlde widens the understanding of medieval moral instruction, religion, reading practices, and education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Ethics.2bisacsh1 aRaymo, Robert, eeditor.1 aSternglantz, Ruth, eeditor.1 aWhitaker, Elaine, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442621022423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442621022.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG